as once called a "corrupter of youth" for an innovation that is now a vital component of elementary school curricula. Set theory has been widely adopted in mathematics and philosophy, but the controversy surrounding it at the turn of the century remains of great interest. Cantor's own faith in his theory was partly theological. His religious beliefs led him to expect paradoxes in any concept of the infinite, and he always retained his belief in the utter veracity of transfinite set theory. Later in his life, he was troubled by recurring attacks of severe depression. Dauben shows that these played an integral part in his understanding and defense of set theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInfinite. 0aSet theoryxHistory. 0aTransfinite numbersxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh  aAristotle.  aArithmetic.  aBerlin, Germany.  aBorchardt, C. W.  aCatholic church.  aConsistency.  aContinuity.  aDerived Set(s).  aDiagonal method.  aEpistemology.  aEquivalence.  aFinitism.  aFourier series.  aGoldscheider, F.  aGrattan-Guinness, I.  aHermite, C.  aJeiler, I.  aJoseph of Arimathea.  aKerry, B.  aKronecker, L.  aLimit points.  aLogic.  aMathematics.  aNeo-Thomism.  aOrder types.  aParadoxes.  aPoint sets.  aPower(s).  aQuaternions.  aSchoenflies, A.  aSet theory.  aSubsets.  aTheologians.  aTransfinite numbers.  aTrigonemetric series.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691214207zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691214207423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691214207.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999 